<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06096004 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06096004 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  MISSOURI; RIVER; BOAT; GAMBLING; MISSISSIPPI; LEGISLATION; ATTEMPT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Missouri voters would get to decide whether riverboat casinos should cruisethe state's Mississippi and Missouri rivers under a bill approved by theHouse.;    Similar bills failed six times last year, but on Thursday the billsqueaked by 82-75, the minimum vote needed.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MISSOURI HOUSE BACKS VOTE ON GAMBLING  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     But the bill faces an uncertain future in the Senate.;    Supporters of thebill said riverboat gambling would boost the economies of river towns acrossthe state. It also would bring about $1.6 million a year into the statetreasury for every gambling boat in operation, they said.;    But opponentssaid that gambling would break up families, increase crime and deceive poorpeople with the glitter of get-rich-quick promises.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  St. Louis Post-Dispatch  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Jefferson City, Mo.  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910405  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  115  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday April 5, 199100096004,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>